<p>For New York City's cold climate, the most effective HVAC systems combine high heating efficiency with adequate cooling capacity. Heat pumps with SEER ratings of 16-20 and HSPF ratings of 9.5 or higher are ideal, as they can efficiently heat homes even when temperatures drop to 15¬∞F. For extremely cold periods, dual-fuel systems that pair heat pumps with gas furnace backup provide optimal comfort and efficiency. Air conditioning systems should have minimum SEER ratings of 16, though 18-20 SEER units offer better value given NYC's high electricity costs. Due to the city's heating-dominant climate, prioritize systems with strong heating performance‚Äîresidents typically spend 60-70% of their HVAC energy on heating versus 30-40% on cooling. Ductless mini-split systems are particularly popular in NYC apartments and older buildings where ductwork installation is challenging, offering zone control that can reduce energy waste by 20-30%.</p>

